The RMSE and runtimes for all three data sets are shown in table 1. As expected, KR, GPR and rBCM outperform the identity-baseline (p < 10−3 for both data sets), supporting H1. 1-NN outperforms the baseline only in the Barabási-Albert data set (p < 10−3). Also, our results lend support to H2 as rBCM outperforms 1-NN in both data sets (p < 0.05 for Barabási-Albert, and p < 0.01 for Conway’s Game of Life). However, rBCM is significantly better than KR only for the Barabási-Albert data set (p < 0.001), indicating that for simple data sets such as our theoretical ones, KR might already provide a sufficient predictive quality. Finally, we do not observe a significant difference between rBCM and GPR, as expected in H3. Interestingly, for these data sets, rBCM is slower compared to GP, which is probably due to constant overhead for maintaining multiple models.
